%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{What Are We Trying To Do?}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{frame}{The task}
We train a robot arm to:
\begin{itemize}
  \item pick up a banana in a scene,
  \item move it toward the plate (goal position),
  \item place the banana successfully.
\end{itemize}

The robot is simulated in PyBullet using a Panda-gym based environment.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Why we need learning (intution first)}
We want a neural policy:
\begin{itemize}
  \item It observes the current state of the robot and banana,
  \item produces an action (robot movement + gripper command),
  \item repeats until either success or time limit.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Core idea:} the policy improves because it receives feedback via reward.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{The sparse reward problem}
The environment reward is sparse:
\begin{itemize}
  \item large positive reward only when the banana is placed on the plate,
  \item otherwise a small negative reward each step.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{If the robot starts randomly:}
\begin{itemize}
  \item it rarely succeeds by chance,
  \item it gets almost no useful “directional” learning signal.
\end{itemize}

So we replace that with a learned reward that can guide behavior earlier.
\end{frame}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Data We Have (and what it really means)}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{frame}{Do we have a “database”?}
Conceptually, yes, but it is not like a labeled dataset of “good/bad”.
Instead we have:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Expert demonstrations} (successful episodes)
  \item \textbf{Clips} generated from demos and random rollouts
  \item \textbf{Human preferences} comparing pairs of clips
  \item \textbf{Learned reward weights} obtained from those preferences
  \item \textbf{Replay buffer} (a dataset of transitions used by RL)
\end{itemize}

Each part plays a role in making learning possible.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{What is inside an expert demo?}
An expert demo contains one \textbf{episode trajectory} with tensors over time:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \texttt{state\_trajectory}: state at each step
  \item \texttt{action\_trajectory}: action taken at each step
  \item \texttt{next\_state\_trajectory}: next state after each action
  \item \texttt{done\_trajectory}: whether the episode ended at that step
\end{itemize}

In other words, it is a sequence of transitions $(s_t, a_t, s_{t+1}, done_t)$.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{What is the state / action?}
The environment state is a dictionary with:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \texttt{observation}: robot + banana information (20 dims)
  \item \texttt{achieved\_goal}: banana position (3 dims)
  \item \texttt{desired\_goal}: fixed target plate position (3 dims)
\end{itemize}

Action is a continuous vector controlling:
\begin{itemize}
  \item end-effector displacement (dx,dy,dz),
  \item gripper command.
\end{itemize}

So the problem is: learn the mapping state $\rightarrow$ action.
\end{frame}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Phase 1.1 — Generate Clips + Design Features}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{frame}{What Phase 1.1 requires}
We must generate 30 trajectory clips:
\begin{itemize}
  \item 20 from \textbf{expert demos}
  \item 10 from \textbf{random actions}
\end{itemize}

And we must compute a \textbf{feature vector} for each trajectory.
These features are what the reward learning will later weight.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Step-by-step: what \texttt{banana.py} does}
\textbf{Step 1:} load expert demos from \texttt{demo\_data/PickAndPlace}

\textbf{Step 2:} for each demo episode
\begin{itemize}
  \item replay the demo in the environment,
  \item render frames and save an MP4 clip,
  \item compute features $\phi(\tau)$ from the whole episodic trajectory.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Step 3:} generate 10 random episodes
\begin{itemize}
  \item sample random actions each time step,
  \item save the clips,
  \item compute features for those bad trajectories too.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{What are “features” and why do we need them?}
We cannot directly learn a reward function from raw physics.
Instead, we define a \textbf{hand-engineered feature map}:
\[
\phi(\tau) = [f_1(\tau), f_2(\tau), f_3(\tau)]
\]

Each $f_i(\tau)$ measures something meaningful about the trajectory, like:
\begin{itemize}
  \item did the arm approach the banana?
  \item did the banana approach the plate?
  \item did it end close to the goal?
\end{itemize}

The learned reward will be:
\[
R(\tau) = w^\top \phi(\tau)
\]
where $w$ is learned from preferences.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Where $\phi(\tau)$ comes from (intuitive view)}
In our implementation, the features are based on distances:
\begin{itemize}
  \item distances from end-effector to banana,
  \item distances from banana to plate (min and final).
\end{itemize}

We negate distances so that:
\begin{itemize}
  \item smaller distance $\Rightarrow$ larger reward feature value.
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Phase 1.2 — Preference Learning with APReL}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{frame}{What Phase 1.2 requires}
A human teacher compares trajectories by watching clips.
For each comparison:
\begin{itemize}
  \item the system shows two trajectory clips,
  \item the human chooses which one is preferred.
\end{itemize}

We are limited to \textbf{10} total queries.

The goal is to infer the reward weights $w$ that make the preferred trajectory score higher.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Step-by-step: what \texttt{pref\_learn.py} does}
\textbf{Step 1:} convert the saved clip records into an APReL \texttt{TrajectorySet}.
Each trajectory has a feature vector $\phi(\tau)$.

\textbf{Step 2:} initialize a belief over weights:
\begin{itemize}
  \item APReL maintains a distribution of possible $w$ values consistent with previous answers.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Step 3:} repeat for 10 queries:
\begin{itemize}
  \item choose a pair of trajectories to ask about (using an acquisition function),
  \item show clips to the human,
  \item human selects the preferred one,
  \item update the belief/posterior using that preference.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Step 4:} output posterior mean weights $w$ and save them to:
\texttt{saved/feature\_weights.csv}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{How the human feedback “teaches” reward}
Suppose the human picks trajectory A over B.
Intuitively, we want:
\[
w^\top \phi(\tau_A) > w^\top \phi(\tau_B)
\]

Across 10 comparisons, APReL finds weights $w$ that best explain why the human consistently preferred the chosen clips.
That is why we needed both good (experts) and bad (random) trajectories:
random ones provide contrast.
\end{frame}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Phase 2 — RL from Demonstrations (episodic training)}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{frame}{What Phase 2 requires (the assignment loop)}
The assignment asks for an \textbf{episodic training loop}:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Roll out the current policy for one full episode.
  \item Recover reward for that episode using the learned reward weights.
  \item Store the transitions into a replay buffer.
  \item Update the policy.
\end{enumerate}

This differs from “standard RL” which mixes rewards step-by-step from env output.
Here we do \textbf{post-hoc reward recovery} from the entire episode.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Step-by-step: what \texttt{policy\_learn.py} does (SAC)}
\textbf{Step 0:} pre-fill replay buffer with 20 expert demos
\begin{itemize}
  \item For each expert episode, compute $R(\tau)=w^\top\phi(\tau)$,
  \item distribute it across steps to create per-step rewards,
  \item add transitions to the buffer.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Step 1:} roll out ONE episode using the current SAC policy
\begin{itemize}
  \item collect $\{(s_t, a_t)\}$ as trajectory pairs (for $\phi(\tau)$),
  \item collect transition tuples $(s_t,a_t,s_{t+1},done_t)$ for the replay buffer.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Step 2:} recover episode reward post-hoc
\begin{itemize}
  \item compute $\phi(\tau)$ from trajectory pairs,
  \item compute $R(\tau)=w^\top \phi(\tau)$,
  \item define $r_t = R(\tau)/T$ for each step $t$.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Step 3:} train SAC using off-policy updates from the replay buffer.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{How can the robot learn from the expert demos?}
Because expert demos provide valuable transitions early:
\begin{itemize}
  \item the replay buffer initially contains behavior close to success,
  \item critics learn value estimates on those state-action pairs,
  \item actors learn to improve toward higher-value actions.
\end{itemize}

So the robot does not start learning from scratch.
It starts from something like “good behavior already exists in memory”.
Then RL improves it.
\end{frame}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{SAC vs AWAC (what to say in the report)}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{frame}{SAC (conceptual summary)}
SAC is an actor-critic method with entropy regularization:
\begin{itemize}
  \item critic learns $Q(s,a)$ (value),
  \item actor learns a policy that picks actions with higher $Q$,
  \item entropy encourages exploration.
\end{itemize}

It’s general-purpose and strong when you have a reasonable reward signal.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{AWAC (conceptual summary)}
AWAC is another actor-critic method but its actor update is special:
\begin{itemize}
  \item it computes an advantage $A(s,a)=Q(s,a)-V(s)$,
  \item it assigns higher weight to actions that have positive advantage,
  \item it pulls the policy toward demo-like “good” actions more strongly.
\end{itemize}

This makes it a good choice for imitation / RLfD settings.
\end{frame}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Evaluation + Visualization}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{frame}{What success means (how we measure learning)}
We evaluate the learned policy by running multiple test episodes:
\begin{itemize}
  \item reset environment randomly,
  \item roll out deterministic policy,
  \item count success when \texttt{info["is\_success"] = True}.
\end{itemize}

We report:
\[
\text{success rate} = \frac{\#\text{successful episodes}}{\#\text{episodes}}
\]
averaged over 10 runs.
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{What plots you can show}
To compare SAC vs AWAC, we track:
\begin{itemize}
  \item success rate over environment steps,
  \item episode reward (mean trajectory reward),
  \item episode length,
  \item actor loss and critic loss (optimization signals).
\end{itemize}

These come from the metrics CSVs generated during training.
\end{frame}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Conclusion}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{frame}{Conclusion (what to write in your report)}
We solved sparse reward learning by:
\begin{itemize}
  \item designing trajectory-level features $\phi(\tau)$,
  \item using APReL + human preferences to learn reward weights $w$,
  \item converting those weights into a dense, episode-based reward,
  \item training RL policies from expert demonstrations with an episodic loop.
\end{itemize}

Then we compare SAC vs AWAC using the same evaluation metric.
\end{frame}

